{{Infobox person | name = Adolf Iosifovich Charlemagne | image = Portrait of the painter Adolf Charlemagne.jpg | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1826|12|8}} | birth_place = [[Saint Petersburg]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1901|1|31|1826|12|8}} | death_place = [[Saint Petersburg]] | nationality = Russian | other_names = | occupation = Painter | years_active = | known_for = | notable_works = }}
[[File:Suvorov Gotthard.jpg|thumb|300px|Field Marshal Suvorov in [[Gotthard Pass]].]] '''Adolf Iosifovich Charlemagne''', or '''Sharleman''' (Russian: Адольф Иосифович Шарлемань; 8 December 1826, [[Saint Petersburg]] - 31 January 1901, Saint Petersburg) was a Russian painter of historical, [[Genre art|genre]] and battle scenes. He was also the creator of a popular design for playing cards known as the "[[Russian playing cards#Design|Satin Deck]]".<ref>[http://www.ukrcards.com.ua/poleznoe-show-5.html Brief biography] @ House of Cards.</ref>
== Biography == His father was the architect, {{ill|Iosif Ivanovich Charlemagne|ru|Шарлемань, Иосиф Иванович}}. His grandfather, the sculptor and decorative artist, Jean-Baptiste Charlemagne-Baudet (1734-1789), was originally from [[Rouen]] and had come to Russia to work for [[Catherine the Great]].<ref name="R">[http://www.artsait.ru/art/sh/sharleman/main.htm Brief biography] @ Russian Paintings.</ref> His brother, [[Iosif Iosifovich Charlemagne|Iosif]], also became an artist and architect.
He received his primary education at [[Saint Peter's School]], then enrolled at the [[Imperial Academy of Arts]], where he studied history painting with [[Fyodor Bruni]] and battle painting with [[Bogdan Willewalde]].<ref name="R" /> While there, he was awarded several silver and gold medals.
The last of these awards, in 1855, carried with it a stipend to study abroad. He went to Munich, where he studied with [[Alexander Kotzebue]], another battle painter. In 1859, he was named an "Academician" for his portrayals of [[Alexander Suvorov]] in the Swiss Alps. He then went to Paris and studied the paintings at [[Versailles]]. He returned to Saint Petersburg by way of Germany in 1861.
His first paintings after returning were for the [[Page Corps]], followed by ceiling murals at the [[Meshchersky|Meshchersky family]] mansion in Moscow.<ref name="R" /> In 1867, his portrayal of Catherine the Great in the workshop of [[Étienne Maurice Falconet]] earned him the title of Professor. It was acquired by Empress [[Maria Alexandrovna (Marie of Hesse and by Rhine)|Maria Alexandrovna]]. For the next twenty years, he worked prolifically to supply the demand for his images; many of which became illustrations in magazines. From 1871, he worked for the [[Goznak|Federal State Unitary Enterprise]], designing securities, bonds and other negotiables.<ref name="R" />
